[Event "Baker Bridge - Preemptive Bids"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:83.KQT8742.862.5 QJ42.6.KQJ5.JT62 AK76.J53.94.A874 T95.A9.AT73.KQ93"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
3H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 0, nRot: 0, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "02f2f3812266079072115d59901b47eecf1a5e7e53ff90a733ea8ab590b5f3e8"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/preemptive_bids"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

No matter how much we try to reduce bridge to rules and guidelines we will never get rid of the judgement factor. With this hand you definitely have 3 fast tricks for partner. In theory he can take 6 of his own, so 3\H should be the right contract. BUT, maybe he could ruff a \D in your dummy?

Fortune favors the bold so you bid 4\H . . . and live happily ever after.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:KQJ98752.9.52.87 A3.732.QJT84.T93 T4.Q86.A963.J642 6.AKJT54.K7.AKQ5"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "211c212707f45cf0da5cd3398e8d7924ce8c7d1c8b87dab864b642a7b2aa3110"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/preemptive_bids"]
[Student "S"]
{You dealt this hand.  

With 7 estimated winners and an 8-card suit you preempt 4\S. And you are not going to make it. In fact you are only going to make 8 tricks so you will go down 2.

You may be wishing that you had opened just 3\S, rather than following the guidelines and opening at the 4-level. The problem with that thinking is that the lower your preempt, the less difficult it is for the opponent's to enter the bidding. If you had opened 3\S South might have been able to make a Takeout Double and they could have found their \H fit. Just visualize their combined hands; they have 9 \Hs between them, they have no \S losers, no \C losers and just one \D loser. If they decide to finesse your partner for the \HQ they can make slam.

This is what preempting is all about.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "S:KQJ9873.6.9842.7 A2.J942.J75.JT52 T6.AKQ85.AK.A864 54.T73.QT63.KQ93"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "6S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
3S pass 6S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 5, chOption: S, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:2, nBasis: 0, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "cac8a8c47f2e3edd2b46df55b8355cb17e8e370fa506d16bbcb9abec7bb164bf"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/preemptive_bids"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

If is hard to imagine any hand partner could have where the slam wouldn't be there. Maybe you should use Blackwood, just to be sure? If partner shows 1 Ace you would then bid 6\S. And if he shows no Aces you would then . . . bid 6\S anyway. So you leave out the middle step and bid 6\S.

Did you think about bidding 6NT instead? Ugh, they would have led a \C.}

